<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-843-358  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 843 358.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Vision Graphics andamp; Image Processing  Sept 1990 v51 n3p275(24).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Refining edges detected by a LoG operator. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ullupinar, Faith; Medioni, Gerard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Processing visual information requires transforming a very largeamount of viewer centered visual input into a meaningful objectcentered description and part of that transformation involvesphysical edges.andP;  Detecting intensity changes is the first step inanalyzing an image.andP;  The Laplacian-of-Gaussian (LoG) operator isused in edge detection, but it has problems.andP;  Ways to correctthese problems are proposed.andP;  A simple test to detect true edgesworks with one-dimensional signals.andP;  The problem of bias can behandled either by combining the results of the convolution of twoLoG operators of different standard deviations or sampling theconvolution with a single LoG filter at two points besides thezero-crossing.andP;  The refining process also can be used to processlinear segments that approximate the detected contours.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer VisionImage ProcessingEdge DetectionGaussian Elimination.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Zero-crossings do not always correspond to edges. (chart)Test for true edges. (chart)Results of the multiresolution method. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>